national organizations garner and conserve power—and how this affects their ability to fulfill their stated missions—will find much of value in The Authority Trap. The authors use case studies that illuminate how INGOs are received by three main audiences: NGO peers, state policymakers, and corporations. In the end, the authors argue, the more authority an INGO has, the more constrained is its ability to affect the conduct of world politics.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 02. Mrz 2022) 0aAuthority. 0aNon-governmental organizationsxPolitical aspects. 0aOrganizational behaviorxPolitical aspects. 0aOrganizational effectivenessxPolitical aspects. 0aReputationxPolitical aspects. 4aInternational Studies. 4aPolitical Science & Political History. 4aSociology & Social Science. 7aPOLITICAL SCIENCE / NGOs (Non-Governmental Organizations).2bisacsh1 aWong, Wendy H., eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertCornell University Press Complete eBook-Package 2017z978311066587140uhttps://doi.org/10.7591/9781501709777zCo-access DOI >> click Walter de Gruyter40uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9781501709777423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9781501709777/original  a978-3-11-066587-1  Cornell University Press Complete eBook-Package 2017b2017  aEBA_BACKALL  aEBA_CL_SN  aEBA_EBACKALL  aEBA_EBKALL  aEBA_ECL_SN  aEBA_EEBKALL  aEBA_ESSHALL  aEBA_PPALL  aEBA_SSHALL  aEBA_STMALL  aGBV-deGruyter-alles  aPDA11SSHE  aPDA12STME  aPDA13ENGE  aPDA17SSHEE  aPDA5EBK